The documentation of [mysqli::query()](https://www.php.net/manual/en/mysqli.query.php) states about the return value :

&gt; Returns FALSE on failure. For successful SELECT, SHOW, DESCRIBE or EXPLAIN queries mysqli_query() will return a mysqli_result object. For other successful queries mysqli_query() will return TRUE.

You are executing a `SELECT` query, and then, in case of success, returns a [mysqli_result](https://www.php.net/manual/en/class.mysqli-result.php) object.

`if( $conn-&gt;query($query) === TRUE ){` will always be false since a `SELECT` query will never return `true`

`$conn-&gt;query($query) === false` **doesn&#39;t mean** that the query returned 0 results, but that the query failed.

You might want to count the number of rows returned. If it&#39;s 0, it means that the query didn&#39;t find any matching result -&gt; login failed, otherwise, the login is success.

Note that your query is vulnerable to SQL injections. You should consider using [prepared statements](https://www.php.net/manual/en/mysqli.quickstart.prepared-statements.php)

