When you have both a command and an entrypoint, Docker runs _only_ the entrypoint, and passes the command to it as arguments.  See [Understand how CMD and ENTRYPOINT interact](https://docs.docker.com/engine/reference/builder/#understand-how-cmd-and-entrypoint-interact) in the Dockerfile docs.  As soon as the entrypoint exits, the container is over; it can do whatever it likes with the command part, including completely ignoring it.

Typical practice is to end the entrypoint script with

&lt;!-- language: lang-sh --&gt;

    exec &quot;$@&quot;

which causes it to just take its command-line arguments and run them as a command, replacing the entrypoint script as the main container process.

Without this, you get to the end of the entrypoint script, and the container has done everything it&#39;s told to do, so it exits successfully (status code 0).

if an optional parameter (the `{_locale}` parameter) is at an optional position (i.e. the end) and is also the default, it can (and apparently will) be omitted. The same is true for `{_format}` and even for `.{_format}` (additional dot)

I think, as long as it works, why do you care?

You can maybe force the parameter by explicitly defining the `_locale` requirement to be `[a-z]{2}` (or even more explicitly `de|en`) but I&#39;m not entirely certain.

